ccessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow is London responding to social and economic crises, and to the challenges of sustaining its population, economy and global status? Sustainable development discourse has come to permeate different policy fields, including transport, housing, property development and education. In this exciting book, authors highlight the uneven impacts and effects of these policies in London, including the creation of new social and economic inequalities. The contributors seek to move sustainable city debates and policies in London towards a progressive, socially just future that advances the public good. The book is essential reading for urban practitioners and policy makers, and students in social, urban and environmental geography, sociology and urban studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aSustainable urban developmentzEnglandzLondon. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Geography.2bisacsh1 aBrown, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDatta, Kavita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDolton, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFournière, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrancis, Robert A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGinn, Franklin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamnett, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerrick, Clare, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHickman, Robin, econtributo